Our data isnt in tidy format. Each lobster should have an individual row. The data is currently presented in a frequency table!

Lets expand this using the tidyr::uncount function for lobster counts. This function drops NAs! Careful.

lobster_tidy <- lobster_abundance %>%
  uncount(lobster_count)

Yay! Now each lobster has its own row. This is tidy format!

But lets explore this data a bit morelike by date!

Use lubridate to parse date and times: Always use lubridate:: because lubridate functions are redundant

Lets add a new column with mutate() that contains a date with an actual date

# Let's get R to recognize dates as a date.
# Date currently stored as month / day / year (mdy). Remember this!

lobster_date <-  lobster_tidy %>% 
  mutate(
    date_new = lubridate::mdy(date)
  )

# Both date format and variable class have changed.

Can we group this by months? Sure can!

Parse date_new column to get different pieces separated. label = TRUE gives you month abbreviation

lobster_parse_date <- lobster_date %>%
  mutate (
    obs_month = lubridate::month(date_new, label = TRUE)
  ) %>% 
  mutate (
    obs_year = lubridate::year(date_new)
  )

Nice!

This is super important when considering sample sizes.

How do we find numbers of observations in a summary table? use group_by + summarize + n()

lobster_summary <- lobster_parse_date %>%
  group_by (site) %>%
  summarize(
    mean_size = mean(size_mm, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_size = sd(size_mm, na.rm = TRUE),
    sample_n = n()
  )

Count basically is better than tally. Dont listen to tally people.

Lets start looking at some confidence intervals and t-tests.

T distribution accounts for increased uncertainty with small sample sizes and population uncertainty.

Use the t.test() function to find confidence intervals and perform t-tests pull() stores values as a vector. Useful for some base r functions.

# Let's find CI for lobster sizes at IV beach

ivee_lobsters <- lobster_tidy %>%
  filter(site == "IVEE") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)

t.test(ivee_lobsters)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  ivee_lobsters
## t = 245.23, df = 2302, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  72.99130 74.16806
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  73.57968

Okay, but lets see if theres a significant difference in size between lobsters measured at naples and mowhawk reef

First, the tedious way

# Don't put just single means in! You need entire sample.

napl_sample <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "NAPL") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)

mohk_sample <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "MOHK") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)
  
mohk_napl_ttest <- t.test(mohk_sample, napl_sample)

mohk_napl_ttest
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mohk_sample and napl_sample
## t = -19.849, df = 1850.8, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -12.43436 -10.19806
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  66.86833  78.18454

What does this mean? There is a 2.2 e -16 chance that if I took two random samples from a population with the same mean that I would get means this different. So, actually, whats more likely is that the two sample populations were initially different.

Inline variable referencing:

Lets make a statement about the t-test.

Mean lobster size differed significantly between Mohawk and Naples reefs (df(1850.7720862), t = -19.8487322)

But theres an easier way!!

# Create df with two groups you want to compare

lobster_2 <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == c("NAPL", "MOHK"))

ttest_2 <- t.test(size_mm ~ site, data = lobster_2)

ttest_2
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  size_mm by site
## t = -14.483, df = 926.81, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -13.24265 -10.08206
## sample estimates:
## mean in group MOHK mean in group NAPL 
##           66.59490           78.25725
